headline: Wall Street Shaken by Auto Sector Bankruptcies
summary: A pair of high-profile bankruptcies in the auto space First Brands Group and Tricolor Holdings LLC has rattled Wall Street in recent weeks. Jeff Sherman, deputy CIO at DoubleLine Capital, and Amanda Lynam head of macro credit research at BlackRock, discuss credit on "Bloomberg Real Yield".

headline: Business Lookahead: The perils of politics
summary: STORY: From the start of U.S. earnings season to political turmoil in France and Japan, these are the stories to watch in business and finance in the coming days.:: Banks kick off U.S. earningsJPMorgan Chase, Citigroup, Wells Fargo, Goldman Sachs and asset manager BlackRock will report financial results as earnings season kicks off.Investors are counting on solid profits to support record-high stock prices.According to LSEG data, S&P 500 companies are expected to post an 8.8% rise in third-quarter earnings on a year-over-year basis.Financial sector earnings are expected to increase almost 13%.:: A new 'sick man'France might be the new 'sick man of Europe,' with one of the biggest budget deficits in the bloc, a weak economy, and a political crisis on its hands. Time is running out to get the 2026 budget through a fractured parliament.French bonds and stocks have recovered slightly, but the prognosis remains grim.If the next government swells the deficit, it won't sit well with Brussels, ratings agencies and bond vigilantes.:: Changing the guardSanae Takaichi, leader of the Liberal Democratic Party, looked set to become Japan's first female prime minister in a parliament vote set for Wednesday.But that date will likely be pushed back after Japan's Komeito party pulled its support for the hardline conservative, breaking a 26-year-old alliance.The uncertainty is set to stoke worries about the outlook for one of the world's most indebted countries.:: Policymakers converge on D.C.Policymakers head to Washington for the annual International Monetary Fund and World Bank meetings with no shortage of hot topics to discuss. The IMF's World Economic Outlook will be released on Tuesday, among other reports. On the sidelines, Argentina's President Javier Milei will meet U.S. President Donald Trump at the White House as final details of Washington's $20 billion-dollar lifeline for Buenos Aires are eagerly anticipated.
